    Work is zero if force is perpendicular to motion. Force is in the same direction as <math xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" xmlns:fo="urn:oasis:names:tc:opendocument:xmlns:xsl-fo-compatible:1.0" xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:md="http://cnx.rice.edu/mdml" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mtext mathvariant="bold">E</mtext></mrow><mrow/></mrow><annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12&#123;E&#125; &#123;&#125;</annotation></semantics></math>, so that motion along an equipotential must be perpendicular to <math xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" xmlns:fo="urn:oasis:names:tc:opendocument:xmlns:xsl-fo-compatible:1.0" xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:md="http://cnx.rice.edu/mdml" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mtext mathvariant="bold">E</mtext></mrow><mrow/></mrow><annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12&#123;E&#125; &#123;&#125;</annotation></semantics></math>. More precisely, work is related to the electric field by
    
